statement:
Determine, with explanation, whether the series

\begin{align*}\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^{n}}{n(\ln n)^{101}}\end{align*}

converges absolutely, converges conditionally, or diverges.

sols:
We will use the integral test. Note that

\begin{align*}\int_2^\infty \frac{dx}{x\ln(x)^{101}}=\lim_{a\to \infty} \int_2^a \frac{dx}{x\ln(x)^{101}}\end{align*}

We can calculate $\int_2^a \frac{dx}{x\ln(x)^{101}}$ by substitution
with $u=\ln x$ (then \emph{du=(1/x)dx}) to get

\begin{align*}
\int_2^a \frac{dx}{x\ln(x)^{101}} &= \int_{\ln(2)}^{\ln(a)} u^{-101}du \\
&= \left.-\frac1{100u^{100}}\right|_{\ln(2)}^{\ln(a)} \\
&= -\frac1{100}\left(\frac1{(\ln(a))^{100}}-\frac1{(\ln(2))^{100}}\right) \end{align*}

Hence

\begin{align*}\int _2^\infty \frac{dx}{x\ln(x)^{101}}=\lim_{a\to \infty} \frac1{100}\left(\frac{1}{\ln(2)^{100}}-\frac{1}{\ln(a)^{100}}\right)=\frac{1}{100\ln(2)^{100}}.\end{align*}

This implies that the series converges absolutely by the integral test.
